properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A cluster of severe thunderstorms over Southeastern Manitoba is moving east at 55 km/h. Torrential rainfall with localized flooding, loonie size hail and wind gusts to 90 km/h have been reported in Manitoba under these thunderstorms. Locations impacted include: Lake of the Woods Provincial Park, Sioux Narrows, Sioux Narrows Provincial Park, and Nestor Falls. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of dangerous thunderstorms that may be capable of producing strong wind gusts, damaging hail and heavy rain. Thunderstorms are moving eastwards across southwestern Manitoba this morning. Some of these thunderstorms will likely be severe, capable of damaging hail, strong winds, and torrential rainfall. The activity will move out of the region on Friday morning, but another round of severe thunderstorm activity will develop later in the day, potentially impacting far southeastern Saskatchewan into southern Manitoba. ### Very large hail can damage property, break windows, dent vehicles and cause serious injury. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Tropical Cyclone Information Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: For Post-tropical Storm Humberto. The next information statement will be issued by 03:00 p.m. ADT. Gale to storm force winds have moved into the southeastern Maritime waters and will spread across the southern Grand banks today and tonight. 1. Summary of basic information at 09:00 a.m. ADT. Location: Near 41.9 North 57.6 West. About 300 kilometres southeast of Sable Island. Maximum sustained winds: 120 kilometres per hour. Present movement: Northeast at 35 kilometres per hour. Minimum central pressure: 973 millibars. 2. Public weather impacts and warnings summary. No significant effects are expected over land. a. Wind. No significant wind expected. b. Rainfall. Heavy bands of rain will approach and may reach portions of the Avalon Peninsula as Post-Tropical Storm Humberto tracks across the Grand Banks tonight and early Saturday morning. c. Surge/Waves. Swells of 2 to 3 metres will reach the Atlantic coast of Nova Scotia by late this morning, and 3 to 5 metre swells will then reach southern Newfoundland tonight and early Saturday. Waves will break higher along some areas of the coastline, and dangerous rip currents are possible. 3. Marine weather impacts and warnings summary. Storm warnings are in effect for East Scotian Slope - eastern half, Laurentian Fan, Southwestern Grand Banks and Southeastern Grand Banks. Gale warnings are in effect for Sable - eastern half, East Scotian Slope - western half, Banquereau - southern half, Northeast Coast and East Coast of Newfoundland, Funk Island bank and the Northern Grand Banks. Gale to Storm Force winds are forecast over southeastern portions of the Maritimes marine district today and over marine areas south and east of Newfoundland later today and Saturday. Hurricane force gusts are expected just south of the track this morning and possibly within the stronger convection that has fired up northwest of the centre. Large waves of 7 to 10 metres will build over offshore waters today and tonight. Some of these waves could exceed 10 metres southeast of the track as the centre passes over Laurentian Fan and the southern Grand Banks. Forecaster(s): Hatt/McArthur. ### Please continue to monitor alerts issued by the Canadian Hurricane Centre and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2019-09-21T17:33:35-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-09-20T11:34:35-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2429056240.2019
Area: Avalon Peninsula Southeast, Avalon Peninsula Southwest

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of severe thunderstorms that may be capable of producing strong wind gusts, large hail and heavy rain. Severe thunderstorms are possible this afternoon into Saturday morning. Thunderstorms are forecast to develop this afternoon. Another round of severe thunderstorms is possible later this evening into tomorrow morning. The main threats are torrential rainfall, wind gusts up to 90 km/h, and loonie sized hail. ### Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
